      {"@type":"Question","name":"How long does new concrete take to cure before I can drive or park on it?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Light foot traffic after 24–48 hours. Wait 7 days before parking passenger vehicles, and 28 days for full design strength. Cold weather may extend timelines."}},
      {"@type":"Question","name":"Do you recommend sealing exterior concrete in Minnesota?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes—freeze/thaw cycles and de-icing salts are harsh. A breathable penetrating sealer repels moisture and chlorides without trapping vapor."}},
      {"@type":"Question","name":"Interior drain tile vs. exterior waterproofing—what’s better?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Both work; choice depends on access and symptoms. Interior drain tile with sump relieves hydrostatic pressure; exterior membranes excel with full perimeter access."}},
      {"@type":"Question","name":"Do I always need a sump pump with drain tile?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes—tile routes water to a basin; the pump discharges it away from the foundation. Include check valve, dedicated circuit, and battery backup."}},
      {"@type":"Question","name":"What are early warning signs of foundation movement?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Diagonal drywall cracks, sticking doors, floor slope, exterior step cracks, trim gaps, chimney separation."}}
    ]}
  </script>
</Layout> 